    <text>
        <body>
            <div type=”letter”>
                <opener><dateline><date when="1915-09-11">September 11, 1915.</dateline></date>
                    <salute>Dear <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet:&ndash;</persName></salute></opener>
               
                <p> I received your check for <measure type="currency" num="70"> $70</measure>. today, for which many thanks. 
                    But I think, my dear, that it is not right. You wrote me a letter some time in the spring telling me that you had cut down 
                    your rates, and that you could only pay me <measure type="currency" num="77">$77 </measure>for this group. At last, I think 
                    you said <measure type="currency" num="77">$77</measure>., but my files are in <placeName key="brookline">Brookline</placeName>, and I cannot get hold of 
                    your letter until I move down in about two weeks. I may be wrong, but my impression is that is what you offered and what I agreed to take.
                    I wish you would look it up, and if I am wrong drop me a line to tell me so, and if I am right, just send me 
                    a check for the extra <measure type="currency" num="7">$7</measure>. </p>
                <p> We had a little symposium here <date when="1915-09-10"> last night</date>. <persName key="ea_robinson"> Edward [sic] Arlington Robinson,</persName>
                    <persName key="randolph_bourne">Randolph Bourne</persName>, who writes for the <title key="newRepublic" level="j">&quote;New Republic,&quote;</title>
                    <persName key="frothingham_eugenia">Eugenia Frothingham</persName>, and I. Bourne said that he 
                    thought <title key="leadSoldiers" level="a">&quote;Lead Soldiers&quote;</title> and Robinson&apos;s
                    poem stood cut above every other poem in your last number, and we each read our own to the others. It was quite a little love feast.</p>
                <p> This is simply a supplement to <date when="1915-09-10"> yesterday&apos;s </date> letter, as I only got your letter this <date when="1915-09-11">morning.</date></p>
                <p> Am glad you had such a nice time on your trip.</p>
                <closer></closer>
            </div>
        </body>
